What Are Conditional Statements?
Conditional statements allow your program to execute different blocks of code based on specific conditions.
  They form the backbone of decision-making in any programming language.

ðŸ”§ Types of Conditional Statements in JavaScript
1. if Statement
Executes a block of code only if the condition is true.

javascript
let age = 20;

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("You are eligible to vote.");
}
âœ… If age is 20, the condition age >= 18 is true â†’ prints the message.

âŒ If age is 16, nothing happens.

2. if...else Statement
Provides an alternative path if the condition is false.

javascript
let score = 45;

if (score >= 50) {
  console.log("You passed.");
} else {
  console.log("You failed.");
}
If score is 45 â†’ prints "You failed."

If score is 60 â†’ prints "You passed."

3. if...else if...else Ladder
Used when you need to check multiple conditions in sequence.

javascript
let marks = 85;

if (marks >= 90) {
  console.log("Grade: A");
} else if (marks >= 80) {
  console.log("Grade: B");
} else if (marks >= 70) {
  console.log("Grade: C");
} else {
  console.log("Grade: D");
}
Checks each condition from top to bottom.

Executes the first block where the condition is true.

4. switch Statement
Best for checking a variable against multiple discrete values.

javascript
let day = "Wednesday";

switch (day) {
  case "Monday":
    console.log("Start of the week");
    break;
  case "Wednesday":
    console.log("Midweek");
    break;
  case "Friday":
    console.log("Weekend is near");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Just another day");
}
Each case is matched against day.

break prevents fall-through to the next case.

default runs if no case matches.

5. Ternary Operator (? :)
A compact alternative to if...else for simple conditions.

javascript
let isLoggedIn = true;

let message = isLoggedIn ? "Welcome back!" : "Please log in.";
console.log(message);
If isLoggedIn is true â†’ prints "Welcome back!"

If false â†’ prints "Please log in."

ðŸ§ª Real-World Example: Login Validation
javascript
let username = "admin";
let password = "1234";

if (!username || !password) {
  console.log("Missing credentials");
} else if (username === "admin" && password === "1234") {
  console.log("Login successful");
} else {
  console.log("Invalid credentials");
}
Uses multiple conditions to validate user input.

Combines if, else if, and else for full control.
